Consider the logic for a second...

    if (number &lt; 1 || number &gt; 3) {
        // Invalid
    } else if (number &gt; 1 &amp;&amp; number &lt; 3) {
       // Valid
    }

Now consider `number` equals `1`.  

* `1` isn&#39;t `&lt; 1` or `&gt; 3`, so we don&#39;t need to do the first statement 
* `1` isn&#39;t `&gt; 1`, but is less `&lt; 3` (but it&#39;s an `and`, so `1` isn&#39;t `&gt; 1` AND `&lt; 3`) so we don&#39;t need to do the second statement 
* Um, why am I here?

So, you&#39;d better of doing something like...

    if (number &lt; 1 || number &gt; 3) {
        // Invalid
    } else if (number &gt;= 1 &amp;&amp; number &lt;= 3) {
       // Valid
    }

But, you&#39;ve basically done the range check in the first statement, so you could actually do something like...

    if (number &lt; 1 || number &gt; 3) {
        // Invalid
    } else {
       // Valid
    }

or 

    if (number &gt;= 1 &amp;&amp; number &lt;= 3) {
        // Valid
    } else {
       // Invalid
    }

or, frankly just do...

    if (number == 1) {
        // Do number 1 option
    } else if (number == 2) {
        // Do number 2 option
    } else if (number == 3) {
        // Do number 3 option
    } else {
        // Invalid
    }

This commonly known as &quot;happy path&quot; - you do what you&#39;re expecting first and then handle the &quot;how did I get here!?&quot; cases lasts.

I just want to point out that &quot;desk checking&quot; your code is really, really important for catching these kind of issues.  You could also use `print` statements are even run through the debugger, all of which will help you better understand what you&#39;ve done wrong. &#129322;&#128521;

